FLOOD CUP

The Flood Cup is the club's most prestigious tournament. It was named in the memory of Cyril Grosvenor Flood, a noted club member who passed away on September 10, 1978.
The cup was first awarded retrospectively to Nev Cobbold in recognition of the fact that he had been the strongest player in 1978 and over previous years.
Contest for the Flood Cup first occurred in 1979 and has occurred annually ever since.

The Flood Cup is usually run as a 7 round Swiss tournament, or a round-robin when there are 12 entries or less.

A notable exception was the 1983 Flood Cup, awarded for best performance over several of the club's tournaments (similar to the present day Best All-Rounder Trophy).

In 1996 the Flood Cup was run as a 14 player round-robin, a monumental exercise unlikely to be repeated.

 

Until 2003, Time controls for the Flood Cup were 40 moves in 100 minutes, followed by 10 moves for each subsequent 20 minutes.

Since 2004 time controls have been 80 minutes plus one minute per move from move 1 (except for 2010 only when controls were 60 min + 30 sec).

STUART WILSON TROPHY

(including the One Hour tournament)

The trophy for this tournament was donated to the club in 1993 by Stuart Wilson.

Prior to 1993 a few minor tournaments were held with a time control of an hour per player.

In 1994 a one hour tournament was not held, so the first contest for this new trophy occurred in 1995.

The tournament continued to be known as the 'One Hour' for many years as the time control remained 60 minutes with a guillotine finish until 2004.

Since the 2005 tournament, time controls have been 60 minutes plus ten seconds per move from move 1.

ALLEGRO TOURNAMENT

(10 min+10 sec/move)

The club has run an Allegro tournament since at least as far back as 1983.

Since its inception in 1985, the Best All-Rounder Trophy has always included the Allegro Tournament as a component.

Until 2003, time controls for the Allegro were 15 minutes flat to complete all moves.

From 2004 onwards time controls have been 10 minutes plus 10 seconds per move from move 1.

LIGHTNING TOURNAMENT

(5 minutes)

The club has run a Lightning Tournament since at least as far back as 1983.

Since its inception in 1985, the Best All-Rounder Trophy has always included the Lightning Tournament as a component.

The time control for this tournament has always been the traditional five minute for each player with a guillotine finish.

45 MINUTE TOURNAMENT

The 45 Minute Tournament started as an informal tournament allowing casual attendees and junior players the chance to play competitively in a senior competition.

After 2003 the 45 Minute was elevated to the status of a permanent tournament involving all club players, and was regularly played in a group stage format followed by play-offs to determine the top four places.

This tournament was discontinued after the 2014 edition was abandoned.

St DAVID'S DAY TOURNAMENT

A tournament is held every St David's Day (or the closest Friday to it) to contest the St David's Day Trophy which was donated to the club by Brian Willcock in 2004 to 'celebrate the Welsh heritage of the club'.

BEST ALL-ROUNDER TROPHY

The Best All-Rounder Trophy is essentially the Club Championship.

 

Points are awarded to players based on final position in selected club tournaments during the year.

The current four tournaments used to calculate the Best All-Rounder are the Flood Cup, the Stuart Wilson Trophy, the Allegro and the Lightning.

Until 1998, the Handicap tournament was also included in calculations. The Stuart Wilson Trophy has been part of the Best All-Rounder since 1996.

To be eligible to win a player must participate in a certain number of tournaments.

If all tournaments are not held in a year then the trophy is not awarded (such as occurred in 1987, 1990, 1991 and 1993).

It should be noted that the 1983 Flood Cup was awarded based a system similar to the present Best All-Rounder Trophy points system.

JOE TARNAWSKI TROPHY

Joe Tarnawski donated this trophy to the club in 1993.

It has been awarded every subsequent year to the player with the best achievement in the combined Allegro and Lightning tournaments.

A formula is used to calculate the winner based on the percentage of games won in each tournament.

MAIDEN TROPHY

The Maiden Trophy is awarded to the player who finishes highest in the tournament for the Stuart Wilson Trophy and has not previously won a club tournament or trophy.

The trophy was donated to the club by John Granger.

The first contest for the Maiden Trophy in 1986 was run as a 14 player round-robin, a separate tournament in its own right.

Until 1994 it was run in conjunction with the Handicap Trophy, and has since been awarded on performance in the Stuart Wilson Trophy.

HANDICAP TROPHY

The Handicap Trophy was donated by Doug Foster and is awarded to the player with the highest score in the Flood Cup plus handicap score.

A certain number of points is given to each player as a handicap before the start of the tournament, such that each player has an equal chance of winning.

In most editions up until 1998 the Handicap was run as a separate tournament in its own right, but has since been a prize awarded within the Flood Cup tournament.

THE GAP OPEN

The Gap Open was staged annually from 1980 to 2002.

Originally scheduled for October/November, it was run on the Queen's Birthday Weekend every year from 1983 onwards.

Entries were less from 1993 to 2002 mainly because the club staged a separate one day tournament for juniors on the Sunday.

In 2001 the junior tournament attracted 35 entries, outdrawing the Open itself.

The 2001 Gap Open was run as a repechage event for the Queensland Championship with all but the final 8 contesting the Open.

In the final year of the Open in 2002 the junior tournament once again outstripped the Open attracting 40 entries as against 16 in the adult tournament.
